gency: Civilizing Globalization in an Era of Terrorism -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aMany citizens suspect that the ecological, social, cultural, and political costs of free-market globalization are too high. Yet at the same time they often lack the technical knowledge to assess complex proposals intended to deal with these issues. Written by a uniquely diverse group of academics, policy analysts, and activists, Civilizing Globalization presents in clear, non-technical language the dangers of unfettered global markets, as well as a new vision of globalization regulated to respect social and ecological needs. The contributors show that it is morally and practically imperative to begin thinking about how to deal with this crisis. While no one book can provide a single comprehensive and integrated plan, this volume gives direction and highlights the issues that will be debated for years to come.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aGlobalization. 0aMondialisation. 4aPolitics and Law : International Relations. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology / General.2bisacsh1 aBerry, Albert, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCoburn, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCunningham, Frank, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEdstrand, Hans, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFalk, Richard, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGibb, Heather, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKennedy, Joy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLambert, Rob, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aM